Key Annotations — Complete Reference
@EnableWebSecurity
  @Configuration
  @EnableWebSecurity          // activates Spring Security
  public class SecurityConfig { }
  Activates the entire Spring Security framework.

@EnableMethodSecurity
  @Configuration
  @EnableMethodSecurity       // enables method-level security annotations
  public class SecurityConfig { }
  Unlocks @PreAuthorize, @PostAuthorize, @Secured on methods.

@PreAuthorize
  // Evaluated BEFORE method executes
  @PreAuthorize("hasRole('ADMIN')")
  public void deleteUser(Long id) { }

  @PreAuthorize("hasAnyRole('USER', 'ADMIN')")
  public User getProfile(Long id) { }
  
  @PreAuthorize("isAuthenticated()")
  public List<Order> getMyOrders() { }
  
  // SpEL expressions — access method arguments
  @PreAuthorize("#userId == authentication.principal.id or hasRole('ADMIN')")
  public User getUserById(Long userId) { }

@PostAuthorize
  // Evaluated AFTER method executes — check return value
  @PostAuthorize("returnObject.email == authentication.name")
  public User getUser(Long id) {
      return userRepository.findById(id).orElseThrow();
      // if returned user's email ≠ logged-in user → throw AccessDeniedException
  }

@Secured
    // Simpler, older annotation — role names only, no SpEL
    @Secured("ROLE_ADMIN")
    public void deleteAll() { }
    @Secured({"ROLE_USER", "ROLE_ADMIN"})
    public List<Product> getProducts() { }
    @AuthenticationPrincipal
    java// Inject currently logged-in user directly into controller method
    @GetMapping("/profile")
    public ResponseEntity<User> getProfile(
            @AuthenticationPrincipal UserDetails currentUser) {
        return ResponseEntity.ok(userService.findByEmail(currentUser.getUsername()));
    }

@WithMockUser (Testing)
  @Test
  @WithMockUser(username = "alice", roles = {"ADMIN"})
  public void testAdminEndpoint() throws Exception {
      mockMvc.perform(get("/api/admin/users"))
             .andExpect(status().isOk());
  }

JWT — best for stateless REST APIs and microservices, you manage tokens yourself
OAuth2 — best for social login (Google, GitHub) or delegated access to third-party APIs
SAML — best for enterprise SSO with corporate identity providers (Okta, ADFS, Azure AD)
Always use BCryptPasswordEncoder — never store plain passwords
Use @PreAuthorize with SpEL for fine-grained method-level access control
SessionCreationPolicy.STATELESS is essential for JWT — disables server-side sessions

